          "body": "Paul begins not with the practical issue (head coverings) but with a four-rung theological structure: God → Christ → man → woman. The same word *kephale* (head) governs all three relations. Critically, the Father is *kephale* of the Son not by superiority of essence but by relation of order within the Godhead — the same Son who is fully God (John 1:1; Philippians 2:6) submits to the Father in His messianic mission (John 5:19; 1 Corinthians 15:28). If headship in the Trinity entails ontological equality with order, then headship of man over woman likewise entails ontological equality with order. This is the chapter's anti-egalitarian *and* anti-misogynistic foundation in a single move: women are no more inferior to men than the Son is to the Father — but order exists, and worship displays it. Orthodox commentators differ on application (complementarian readings of Grudem and Schreiner vs. egalitarian readings of Fee and Bilezikian), but the trinitarian-analogical structure of 11:3 is the irreducible datum both sides must reckon with."
