          "title": "The Lord's Supper — proclamation, not provision (11:17-26)",
          "body": "The second paragraph shifts from glory-display to body-discernment. The Corinthians' wealthier members were arriving early at the host's house, eating their own well-provisioned meals in the triclinium, and getting drunk before the poor (slaves, day-laborers) arrived from work and found nothing left. The Lord's Supper had become a Roman dinner party with stratification intact. Paul's corrective is to return them to *what he received from the Lord* (11:23) — the dominical institution on the night of the betrayal. The Supper is **proclamation** (*katangellete*, 11:26): you preach the Lord's death every time you eat. It is **covenant**: the cup is the new covenant in His blood, the new-covenant promise of Jeremiah 31 inaugurated. It is **eschatological**: 'until He comes' (11:26) makes the Supper the meal of the interim age. To eat it as a private supper that despises the poor is to deny what the meal proclaims."
