          "body": "The chapter ends with the most sobering passage in Paul's letters on sacramental judgment. Eating in an unworthy manner — that is, the way the Corinthians have just been doing it, with division and contempt for the body — incurs guilt 'against the body and blood of the Lord' (11:27). The prescribed remedy is not abstention but self-examination (*dokimazo*, 11:28). The shocking claim of 11:30 is that many Corinthians are weak, sick, and have died because of how they have handled the Supper — temporal judgment from the Lord on His own people. Yet 11:32 distinguishes this discipline from final condemnation: *we are disciplined by the Lord so that we will not be condemned along with the world.* The believer's eternal security stands; what is at stake is paternal chastisement now, not damnation later. The chapter ends with the simplest of pastoral remedies: *wait for one another* (11:33). The whole theological apparatus serves a concrete imperative — see your sister; see your brother; the gathered body is the body."
